That's actually a good question.
Nations developed by tribal peoples settling in certain areas, and eventually these settlements were around for long enough for the peoples of each area to become genetically distinct.
For a human, this results in subtle differences, and major differences in phenotype, culture, and behavior (take an Englishman, and a Chinaman for the major difference, and an Englishman and a Welsh man for the minor.)

The "standard" mechs (called "Hybrids") are crew-piloted vehicles in two-and four-legged varieties, similar to metal gears in their anatomy, but they are equipped with jump jetpacks as well as front arms that can wield powered melee weapons or use tools.

There are also experimental "Tetsujin", which generally are shaped like humans or animals, use artificial muscles to move and require the pilot to wear a dangerous neuro implant.

Mechs (and many other space/combat vehicles) use cores that tap into an extradimensional power source, allowing them to generate forcefields that need ridiculous firepower to breach, but also allowing them to crack such forcefields easily with a melee weapon.
